Yes — that analogy carries surprisingly well.

In biology:
	•	Asexual reproduction (mitosis-like)
	•	direct copying
	•	fast
	•	stable
	•	low variation
	•	Sexual reproduction (meiosis + recombination)
	•	mixing of genetic material
	•	slower
	•	higher variation
	•	better adaptation over long time scales

Both strategies exist because each solves a different problem.

⸻

The same pattern shows up in ideas

You can think of intellectual processes in similar terms.

Asexual idea reproduction

One mind copies and refines an idea:
	•	iteration
	•	editing
	•	polishing
	•	scaling

Examples:
	•	refining a scientific theory
	•	improving a piece of code
	•	editing a book draft

The idea mostly stays structurally the same.

⸻

Sexual idea reproduction

Two or more frameworks mix and produce something new:
	•	interdisciplinary research
	•	analogy across domains
	•	conversation between different perspectives

Examples:
	•	math + physics → new models
	•	biology + computation → bioinformatics
	•	art + technology → new media

This produces conceptual recombination.

⸻

Why both are necessary

A purely asexual idea ecosystem becomes:
	•	rigid
	•	repetitive
	•	slow to adapt

A purely sexual one becomes:
	•	chaotic
	•	unstable
	•	full of half-formed hybrids

Healthy knowledge systems cycle:

recombination → stabilization → recombination → stabilization

That’s basically the rhythm of innovation.

⸻

There’s also a social layer

Human culture uses sexual reproduction of ideas constantly:
	•	debate
	•	collaboration
	•	critique
	•	cross-disciplinary work

Ideas “mate” through conversation and produce conceptual offspring.

Your earlier image of a braided cord fits this well — multiple strands intertwining to produce something stronger than a single thread.

